      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "f0135bb6-5d33-41e5-aab2-21e9080b76a7",
        "text": "# Third-party evaluations"
      },
      "after": "80814068-2422-4f6d-958a-0916e8e527f8",
      "id": "f0135bb6-5d33-41e5-aab2-21e9080b76a7",
      "date": 1510681113772
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "525faa27-e44b-4f68-916a-3ff86d859955",
        "text": "Consider a situation where the owner of a majority of a public companies decides to buy out the minority shareholders and take the corporation private. What is a fair price? Obviously it is improper (and, typically, illegal) for the majority owner to simply state a price and then have the (majority-controlled) [[board of directors]] approve that price. What is typically done is to hire an independent firm (a third party), well-qualified to evaluate such matters, to calculate a \"fair price\", which is then voted on by the minority shareholders."
      },
      "after": "f0135bb6-5d33-41e5-aab2-21e9080b76a7",
      "id": "525faa27-e44b-4f68-916a-3ff86d859955",
      "date": 1510681116880
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "fbf96127-b184-44c0-9210-bf74e704a4e0",
        "text": "Third-party evaluations may also be used as proof that transactions were, in fact, fair (\"arm's-length ([[Arm's length principle]])\"). For example, a corporation that leases an office building that is owned by the [[CEO]] might get an independent evaluation showing what the market rate is for such leases in the locale, to address the conflict of interest that exists between the [[fiduciary]] duty of the CEO (to the stockholders, by getting the lowest rent possible) and the personal interest of that CEO (to maximize the income that the CEO gets from owning that office building by getting the highest rent possible)."
      },
